items.synopsis: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese says the "mental scars will not go away" for those involved in a fatal bus crash after a wedding at Wandin Valley Estate. Follow live.

title.children: Bus company says it's working with authorities after 10 killed in wedding crash

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Linq Buslines has released a statement following the fatal bus crash that killed 10 passengers and injured more than 20 others. "We are incredibly saddened to learn of the bus crash that has occurred overnight," the company said in a statement. "Our hearts are with everyone involved in this terrible tragedy and we send our deepest condolences to those who have lost loved ones. "We would like to thank the first responders to the scene, the emergency personnel and those who are continuing to assist. " Trauma counselling services have been made available to all staff and their families at Linq Buslines. "We are working with NSW Police and authorities as they investigate. It would be inappropriate for us to comment further while the investigation is underway."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Linq Buslines 'incredibly saddened', working with NSW Police

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Guests had left the wedding of Mitchell Gaffney and Maddy Edsell, with the ABC understanding some of those in attendance were members of the Singleton Roosters Australian Rules football club. liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: NSW Premier Chris Minns says one person is in hospital in a critical condition. "New South Wales Health reports as of 10am, there's 21 patients being treated across four hospitals in New South Wales ," he says. " One patient is in a critical condition and eight patients are in a stable condition at John Hunter Hospital, five patients in a stable condition at Maitland Hospital, five patients are in a stable condition at Calvary matter Newcastle, and two patients are in a stable condition in the RPA in Sydney."
